Introduction to Data Issues

â†³ 6 cells hidden

There is no substitute for knowing your data. Professionally, this can save moving in the wrong direction and wasting time. Let's look at a real example.

â†³ 0 cells hidden

When patients have recovered enough from a serious injury or disease to return home from the hospital, they often require continuing treatments. The use case is a healthcare company that predicts how many home visits from nurses and various therapists are optimal for full recovery. This covers all sorts of diseases and injuries.

â†³ 0 cells hidden

This model, like every predictive model, explicitly makes assumptions because it must optimize to one goal; in this case, returning to health. The key assumption is that more serious diseases or injuries require more treatment. This is accurate for most conditions, however there are exceptions.

â†³ 0 cells hidden

Fractures and strokes were two exceptions that violated this assumption. The model woefully underestimated the amount of care. For example, someone with a broken hip rarely returns to the hospital but requires nursing and physical therapy. The challenge was to modify the model to account for these exceptions.

â†³ 0 cells hidden
Code Text

Fractures were easy to accomodate because the health record measured how well someone could move, put on clothes, and go to the bathroom, measured on a five-point scale. Adding and engineering this data resulted in predictions that agreed with doctors' recommendations. However, strokes proved to be resistant to accurate modeling.

â†³ 0 cells hidden

At this point, the data science team, happy with the fractures win, wanted to dive into the model to solve for strokes. This is where the principal data scientist suggested that they take the data to their subject matter experts (SMEs) that had decades of nursing experience and understand how strokes and their symptoms were recorded. In 30 minutes, it became quite clear that the data was completely insufficient to provide a meaningful signal. As a result, the team and company now understood a limitation of their product. Without understanding the data, the team may have spent weeks trying to squeeze a signal where there was none.

â†³ 0 cells hidden

Outline of the Course:

To ensure higher quality data, we will follow these steps:

  • Load data
  • Identify variables
  • Variable analysis
  • Handling missing values

age: Age is fractional if less than 1. If the age is estimated, it is in the form of xx.5 .


sibsp: The dataset defines family relations in this way:
sibling = brother, sister, stepbrother, stepsister
spouse = husband, wife (mistresses and fiancÃ©s were ignored).


parch: The dataset defines family relations in this way:
parent = mother, father
child = daughter, son, stepdaughter, stepson.


Some children travelled only with a nanny, therefore parch=0 for them.

Step 12: Conditional Probabilities


Let's ask some simple probability questions:


    

  • What was the probability of survival for a child? P(Survived=true | Age<16)
    • 

  • What was the probability of survival for a woman? P(Survived= true | Sex=female)
    • 

  • What was the probability of survival for a man? P(Survived= true | Sex=male)
    • 



For these straightforward probabilities, we can simply take the percentage of the group who survived.


We'll use the first element of the .shape method to extract the number of rows in each DataFrame (.shape returns two integers in an arrayâ€”the first is the row count, the second is the column count of a DataFrame).


All we have to do is divide the number of surviving children by the total number of children to get the percentage chance of survival for children.


Use the ``format() function to get a nice clean percentage.


â†³ 21 cells hidden

             

               
                 Code
               
               
                 Text
               
             

           
# Step 12:
children = newtitan[newtitan['Age'] < 16]
surviving_children = newtitan[(newtitan['Age'] < 16) & (newtitan['Survived'] == 1)]
print(surviving_children.shape)
print(children.shape)
child_chance_of_survival = surviving_children.shape[0] / children.shape[0]
format(child_chance_of_survival, ".0%")

          
          
        

             

               
                 Code
               
               
                 Text

A correlation matrix is a table showing correlation coefficients between variables. Each cell in the table shows the correlation between two variables. The line of 1.00s going from the top left to the bottom right is the main diagonal, which shows that each variable always perfectly correlates with itself. This matrix is symmetrical, with the same correlation is shown above the main diagonal being a mirror image of those below the main diagonal.

Step 13: Missing Data


Let's briefly examine concepts to guide how we treat missing data. Missing values in the dataset can reduce model fit. It can lead to a biased model as the data cannot be analysed completely. Behavior and relationship with other variables cannot be deduced correctly. It can lead to wrong prediction or classification. Missing values may occur due to problems in data extraction or data collection, which can be categorized as MCAR, MAR, and NMAR as in the diagram below:




â†³ 17 cells hidden

             

               
                 Code
               
               
                 Text
               
             

           
Missing values can be treated by deletion, mean/mode/median imputation, KNN imputation, or using prediction models.




â†³ 0 cells hidden

             

               
                 Code
               
               
                 Text
               
             

           
For our purposes, we'll tackle the basics first: deletion of rows and/or columns and then imputation of missing values. Let's first look at missing values using isna().sum() on the original Titanic dataset in the cell below. (This is where keeping the original pays off)

Our basic options are:


    

  • Deleting the observations. One disadvantage is that it reduces the sample size. If more than 70% of the values are missing for a column, then that column can be deleted.
    • 

  • Mean/ Mode/ Median/ Constant Imputation. Imputation is a method to fill in the missing values with calculated ones or a contant value. This is the most frequently used method. For numerical values you can go with mean, and if there are some outliers try median. For categorical values replace the missing entry with the most frequent one.
    •

Missing Data Summary


    

  • If you don't need the column, drop it.
    • 

  • If a variable is highly correlated with others, keep it and impute.
    • 

  • If more than 70% of the data in a column is missing, drop it, unless it's an important analytical measure.
    • 

  • Continuous values may be replaced by mean, median, or mode, depending on the distribution.
    • 

  • Categorical values are imputed by using the distribution and choosing the the largest.
    • 



Later in the course we will do more advanced imputation using statistical models or predictive algorithms.
